WEBVTT

00:01.952 --> 00:03.702
<i>- Last year, a competition
was created</i>

00:03.746 --> 00:05.787
<i>to test the nation's
best bladesmiths.</i>

00:05.831 --> 00:08.165
<i>Thousands responded,
and this year,</i>

00:08.209 --> 00:10.125
<i>craftsmen from
all over the country</i>

00:10.169 --> 00:12.461
<i>and all walks of life
have come forward</i>

00:12.504 --> 00:14.213
<i>for their change
to claim the title.</i>

00:14.256 --> 00:15.797
- I'm going to be the next
"Forged in Fire" champion.

00:15.841 --> 00:17.132
- I want to win!

00:17.176 --> 00:18.383
- It would be
a life-changing moment.

00:18.427 --> 00:20.010
- Welcome to the Forge.

00:20.054 --> 00:22.638
<i>- Now the Forge returns
with challenges</i>

00:22.681 --> 00:25.140
<i>unlike anything
ever seen before.</i>

00:25.184 --> 00:27.309
- You'll be using this.

00:27.353 --> 00:30.145
<i>- Skill and ingenuity will be
pushed to the limit.</i>

00:30.189 --> 00:31.521
<i>Some will rise to the challenge.</i>

00:31.565 --> 00:34.149
- Whoa!
<i>- Some will fall.</i>

00:34.193 --> 00:35.734
<i>But only the best
will be crowned</i>

00:35.778 --> 00:37.486
<i>"Forged in Fire" champions</i>

00:37.529 --> 00:40.489
<i>and take home $10,000.</i>

00:49.208 --> 00:50.832
<i>- My name's Jeff Bridgers.</i>

00:50.876 --> 00:53.252
I've been making blades
for about eight years.

00:53.295 --> 00:54.836
<i>I'm mainly self-taught.</i>

00:54.880 --> 00:58.340
Being a bladesmith,
it's almost meditative.

00:58.384 --> 01:00.175
<i>I kind of get in tune
with all the things</i>

01:00.219 --> 01:01.551
<i>that I have to do.</i>

01:01.595 --> 01:03.470
<i>- My name's Kim Stahl.</i>

01:03.514 --> 01:05.347
<i>I love working with the fire.</i>

01:05.391 --> 01:07.683
I get a lot of my energy and
aggression pounding metal out.

01:07.726 --> 01:09.559
There's not a lot of
women that are doing this

01:09.603 --> 01:12.437
right now, so I'm definitely
competing for the female factor.

01:12.481 --> 01:14.398
- My name is Harry Harkins.

01:14.441 --> 01:16.692
I've been bladesmithing for
a little over four years now.

01:16.735 --> 01:18.527
<i>I learned bladesmithing
through my brother.</i>

01:18.570 --> 01:22.197
He helped me learn to forge
blades and to make knives.

01:22.241 --> 01:23.782
<i>- My name is Craig Cameron.</i>

01:23.826 --> 01:25.784
I started bladesmithing in 2000.

01:25.828 --> 01:28.203
<i>I've done fairly well,
and I've won a few awards.</i>

01:28.247 --> 01:29.538
I'm a very competitive person.

01:29.581 --> 01:31.248
I'm so competitive,

01:31.292 --> 01:34.876
I can't even play Monopoly
with my mother-in-law.

01:34.920 --> 01:36.086
- Good morning, bladesmiths.

01:36.130 --> 01:37.921
Welcome to the Forge.

01:37.965 --> 01:39.881
You are here to engage
in three rounds

01:39.925 --> 01:42.843
of competition designed
to test every aspect

01:42.886 --> 01:47.222
of your edged-weapon-making
capability, from design

01:47.266 --> 01:49.599
to forging to fit and finish.

01:49.643 --> 01:51.601
After each round,
you will hand your work

01:51.645 --> 01:53.437
over to our panel
of expert judges:

01:53.480 --> 01:57.232
American Bladesmith Society
mastersmith J. Neilson,

01:57.276 --> 02:00.610
historical weapons re-creation
specialist David Baker,

02:00.654 --> 02:04.114
edged and impact weapons
specialist, Doug Marcaida.

02:04.158 --> 02:06.408
They will decide which of you
will be the "Forged in Fire"

02:06.452 --> 02:11.621
champion and leave here
with a check for $10,000.

02:11.665 --> 02:13.248
In the crates in front of you,

02:13.292 --> 02:14.583
there are a variety of metals,

02:14.626 --> 02:18.295
some useful,
some not very useful.

02:18.339 --> 02:20.422
Your job is to choose a metal

02:20.466 --> 02:23.133
and forge a blade
of your own design,

02:23.177 --> 02:25.260
in your signature style.

02:25.304 --> 02:27.763
- Oh, man, I don't know enough
about materials

02:27.806 --> 02:30.265
<i>to decipher between tool steel
and mild steel.</i>

02:30.309 --> 02:32.476
It's just not in my wheelhouse.

02:32.519 --> 02:34.853
<i>- I've never dumpster
dived for steel before.</i>

02:34.897 --> 02:39.524
I use very, very high-quality
known steels with known...

02:39.568 --> 02:42.277
With known... everything's known
about 'em.

02:42.321 --> 02:44.613
<i>This is all new for me.</i>

02:44.656 --> 02:47.032
- You must turn
in a finished blade

02:47.076 --> 02:49.951
capable of advancing you
to round two

02:49.995 --> 02:51.912
that is fully hardened.

02:51.955 --> 02:54.122
The blades themselves must fall
within the following

02:54.166 --> 02:56.166
size parameters.

02:56.210 --> 02:58.460
<i>The length of the blade,
not including the tang,</i>

02:58.504 --> 03:01.463
<i>must be
between 10 and 14 inches.</i>

03:01.507 --> 03:03.467
<i>The overall length of the weapon</i>

03:03.509 --> 03:06.802
<i>must not exceed 22 inches.</i>

03:06.845 --> 03:08.303
Keep in mind,
in the second round,

03:08.347 --> 03:11.848
you will have to attach
a handle to that blade.

03:11.892 --> 03:16.895
Your blades will then be tested
in an ice chop and a rope slice.

03:18.899 --> 03:20.357
You will have 20 minutes

03:20.401 --> 03:22.317
to dumpster dive and work
on your designs.

03:22.361 --> 03:25.195
You will have three hours
to forge your blades.

03:25.239 --> 03:27.072
Your time starts now.

03:27.116 --> 03:30.075
<i>[rock music]</i>

03:30.119 --> 03:31.993
- I hope these guys
know what they're doing.

03:32.037 --> 03:33.829
<i>- Those hubcaps, bicycle wheels,</i>

03:33.872 --> 03:35.914
<i>and that sheet steel
are definitely not metals</i>

03:35.958 --> 03:37.999
<i>that can be hardened.</i>

03:38.043 --> 03:39.668
<i>- I like the bicycle wheel
myself.</i>

03:39.711 --> 03:41.628
[laughs]

03:41.672 --> 03:45.882
- So just by choosing the wrong
steel out of this scrap pile,

03:45.926 --> 03:48.051
a smith could put themselves
out of the competition.

03:48.095 --> 03:49.886
<i>- Mm-hmm.</i>

03:49.930 --> 03:52.389
<i>- Which is the difficulty
of this first challenge,</i>

03:52.433 --> 03:54.891
knowing what your materials
come from.

03:54.935 --> 03:57.060
- Is there anything?
- Uh, no.

03:57.104 --> 03:58.687
- No?

03:58.730 --> 04:00.105
- Right or wrong,
I'm going with it.

04:00.149 --> 04:01.773
<i>I've grabbed an axle.</i>

04:01.817 --> 04:04.067
That's what I'm gonna
try to use.

04:04.111 --> 04:05.694
- Harry looks pretty confident.

04:05.737 --> 04:07.946
First piece of metal
he got, he liked it.

04:07.990 --> 04:10.991
<i>- I'm going to make
what I call a cowboy bowie.</i>

04:11.034 --> 04:13.535
<i>A cowboy bowie
will chop your firewood.</i>

04:13.579 --> 04:15.537
It'll cut the potatoes
for your cowboy stew.

04:15.581 --> 04:19.291
And you can get it so sharp
it'll cut your gizzard out.

04:19.334 --> 04:21.209
How long you going...
You going for 14 inches?

04:21.253 --> 04:22.919
- I'm going 13 1/2.

04:22.963 --> 04:25.130
Gonna leave me a little extra
in there.

04:25.174 --> 04:26.923
<i>I grab that wrecking bar.</i>

04:26.967 --> 04:28.717
<i>I'm pretty sure
it's a hardenable steel.</i>

04:28.760 --> 04:30.719
- There's nothing wrong
with the wrecking bar,

04:30.762 --> 04:33.096
but it's a little
on the softer side.

04:33.140 --> 04:35.807
<i>- I'd say my signature blade
would be the bowie knife.</i>

04:35.851 --> 04:37.767
<i>The weapon I'm making
is the Big B.</i>

04:37.811 --> 04:41.396
<i>The Big B
is a chopper-camp knife.</i>

04:41.440 --> 04:42.647
<i>It's the big bitch.</i>

04:42.691 --> 04:44.107
<i>It's a bitch to grind.</i>

04:44.151 --> 04:45.901
It's a bitch to forge.

04:45.944 --> 04:48.111
But in the end, it makes
a really bitchin' knife.

04:48.155 --> 04:51.907
That's what I'm gonna go with.

04:51.950 --> 04:54.075
<i>- I ended up picking a pry bar,</i>

04:54.119 --> 04:56.244
<i>looks like it's a grade 8 bolt.</i>

04:56.288 --> 04:58.955
I just know it's
a really hard piece of steel.

04:58.999 --> 05:04.753
- Jeff has a similar pike
to what Craig chose.

05:04.796 --> 05:07.255
- He should be okay with that.

05:07.299 --> 05:09.424
<i>- I'm gonna try to make a kukri.</i>

05:09.468 --> 05:11.676
<i>The challenge, you know,
of cutting through the rope,</i>

05:11.720 --> 05:13.595
<i>the curvature in the blade</i>

05:13.639 --> 05:16.264
it seemed like
a good blade for it.

05:16.308 --> 05:19.809
- I never do this.

05:19.853 --> 05:21.102
- Kim...

05:21.146 --> 05:22.604
- That's an interesting choice...

05:22.648 --> 05:24.147
- I don't know
if that's hardenable...

05:24.191 --> 05:25.774
- Is that a good steel
to be using?

05:25.817 --> 05:27.901
- I don't know
if it's a hardenable steel.

05:27.945 --> 05:29.194
<i>- I'm going to make something
similar to a chef's knife.</i>

05:29.238 --> 05:30.737
<i>That's my signature blade.</i>

05:30.781 --> 05:33.114
<i>I'm competing
for the female factor.</i>

05:33.158 --> 05:34.616
<i>It's hard to even find gloves
that fit our fingers</i>

05:34.660 --> 05:36.660
and our hand size.

05:36.703 --> 05:38.620
<i>That's something
that's hopefully gonna change</i>

05:38.664 --> 05:41.373
after a lot more women see this
and become passionate about it.

05:41.416 --> 05:42.958
[exhales]

05:43.001 --> 05:46.169
- Bladesmiths, your design
window is now closed.

05:46.213 --> 05:50.173
Your forging time starts now.

05:50.217 --> 05:51.591
- There we go.

05:51.635 --> 05:55.345
<i>[rock music]</i>

05:55.389 --> 05:57.138
<i>We got forges.
We got sparks.</i>

05:57.182 --> 06:00.475
<i>We got a torch going.
I'm liking this.</i>

06:00.519 --> 06:01.810
- All right,
Harry just took about

06:01.853 --> 06:03.812
a 6 1/2,
7-inch piece

06:03.855 --> 06:05.480
of that axle
and put it in the forge...

06:05.524 --> 06:08.191
- Right in the fire.
There you go.

06:08.235 --> 06:09.818
- It's getting hot.

06:09.861 --> 06:11.695
My brother can't be here,
so today with me,

06:11.738 --> 06:15.198
I brought my brother's apron
and my brother's gloves.

06:15.242 --> 06:16.866
This is my way
of picking him up.

06:16.910 --> 06:19.828
And we're gonna
celebrate this together.

06:19.871 --> 06:23.999
I've got a plan, and my plan is,
"Keep it simple, stupid."

06:24.042 --> 06:26.251
Coming through.
Hot metal.

06:26.295 --> 06:28.878
- Harry's our oldest smith
in the shop today,

06:28.922 --> 06:31.715
and he's moving
faster than anybody else.

06:31.758 --> 06:33.216
- I just hope I'm using
the right steel.

06:33.260 --> 06:35.594
That's all I can say.

06:35.637 --> 06:38.430
<i>I like to talk.
I like to help people.</i>

06:38.473 --> 06:39.848
Get 'er, man.

06:39.891 --> 06:41.349
We got this.
We got this.

06:41.393 --> 06:43.977
I'm just a very
extroverted person.

06:44.021 --> 06:45.854
Come on, attagirl.

06:45.897 --> 06:47.397
I'm having the time of my life.

06:47.441 --> 06:48.898
What're you doing, bubba?

06:48.942 --> 06:51.985
- No worries right now.

06:52.029 --> 06:53.778
- And Craig 's saying,
"To heck with it."

06:53.822 --> 06:56.031
He's just jammed that big rod
in the fire.

06:56.074 --> 06:58.867
- It's a lot of metal
to be carrying around.

06:58.910 --> 07:01.202
- I want to win the competition
for my son.

07:01.246 --> 07:03.371
<i>My boy watched the first
season, and he kept telling me,</i>

07:03.415 --> 07:05.040
<i>he said, "Dad,
you need to be on this show."</i>

07:05.083 --> 07:06.708
<i>So I just wanted to show him</i>

07:06.752 --> 07:08.752
that if there's something
you want to do,

07:08.795 --> 07:11.921
go out and do it.

07:11.965 --> 07:14.966
- Craig is showing a lot
of skill.

07:15.010 --> 07:16.259
- He's chugging right along.

07:16.303 --> 07:18.219
- I do like the metal I chose.

07:18.263 --> 07:19.679
I think it's got enough carbon.

07:19.723 --> 07:23.266
I think it's gonna
hold an edge real well.

07:23.310 --> 07:26.227
- So Craig's cutting
all that excess off now.

07:26.271 --> 07:27.911
- That was smart, though.
He had a handle.

07:27.939 --> 07:31.232
He just drew out what he needed.

07:31.276 --> 07:33.568
That was a good move.
- Bring 'er on, baby.

07:33.612 --> 07:35.945
- At least yours
is shaping up pretty nice.

07:35.989 --> 07:38.740
- It's cooling down quick.

07:38.784 --> 07:41.076
- The only one I've seen so far
that's working cold steel

07:41.119 --> 07:43.953
is Jeffrey.

07:43.997 --> 07:46.915
I'm worried that he's
prepping himself for failure.

07:46.958 --> 07:49.918
- That steel seemed
like it cooled down very quick.

07:49.961 --> 07:52.295
- Jeffrey's is starting to not
look like a kukri anymore.

07:52.339 --> 07:53.755
- Yeah, you've lost a lot

07:53.799 --> 07:56.049
of what he was going
for in the dimensions.

07:56.093 --> 07:58.927
- Based on the way
the metal was moving so slowly,

07:58.970 --> 08:02.847
<i>I decided to go with a
drop-point bowie knife instead.</i>

08:02.891 --> 08:04.224
Now we're cooking.

08:04.267 --> 08:07.227
<i>[rock music]</i>

08:07.270 --> 08:08.937
¶ ¶

08:08.980 --> 08:10.271
- Kim 's struggling
a little bit.

08:10.315 --> 08:11.815
- Yeah.

08:11.858 --> 08:13.650
- I feel, like, a little
nervous.

08:13.694 --> 08:15.527
I don't really know
what kind of metal I've got,

08:15.570 --> 08:18.780
and it's taking a while
for me to move it.

08:18.824 --> 08:21.783
I just need to get this metal
moved out as flat as I can.

08:21.827 --> 08:24.619
I feel like I'm not
getting it any flatter.

08:24.663 --> 08:27.288
Do you think I could just
use the rest of his?

08:27.332 --> 08:28.623
- Oh, and switch it up?

08:28.667 --> 08:31.710
- Yeah, scratch this one?

08:31.753 --> 08:33.753
- I don't know.

08:33.797 --> 08:36.673
- Oh, wait,
she's grabbing the wrecking bar.

08:36.717 --> 08:38.299
- Kim 's starting over.

08:38.343 --> 08:40.885
- Contestants can abandon
their original steel

08:40.929 --> 08:42.303
and start over.

08:42.347 --> 08:44.139
<i>- I grab scrap metal from Craig.</i>

08:44.182 --> 08:46.182
I'm switching materials.
I know I'm already behind.

08:46.226 --> 08:48.977
The original metal I was working
with set me back a whole lot.

08:49.020 --> 08:50.979
<i>Now I'm feeling really
flustered on how I can</i>

08:51.022 --> 08:52.355
make up this time.

08:55.318 --> 08:56.860
- I mean, you hate to see
one of the smiths

08:56.903 --> 08:58.987
have to go back to the dumpster,

08:59.030 --> 09:02.073
but it may also
be a very smart move.

09:02.117 --> 09:05.034
<i>- It would've been amazing
to start with that new metal,</i>

09:05.078 --> 09:08.037
but, you know, go with the flow.

09:08.081 --> 09:11.875
- Bladesmiths, you have
90 minutes remaining.

09:11.918 --> 09:16.880
- I'm sure you just amped up
Kim's stress level.

09:16.923 --> 09:21.050
- Hot metal!

09:21.094 --> 09:23.511
Just rock and roll, man.

09:23.555 --> 09:25.889
Attaboy!
Throw them sparks!

09:25.932 --> 09:28.892
- Throw 'em, baby. Throw 'em.
- Grind that thing, man.

09:28.935 --> 09:32.187
- Man, look at the sparks
that Craig is throwing.

09:32.230 --> 09:34.355
- It's like Fourth of July
over there.

09:34.399 --> 09:36.191
Craig is doing
exactly what I was hoping for.

09:36.234 --> 09:38.234
He's spreading out the back end
of that handle,

09:38.278 --> 09:39.861
so you're gonna have a good grip
on there.

09:39.905 --> 09:41.654
It's not gonna move
around at all.

09:41.698 --> 09:44.032
- It's time to move over
to the heat-treating process.

09:44.075 --> 09:46.117
<i>The heat-treating process
is the soul and the heart</i>

09:46.161 --> 09:49.370
<i>of the blade.</i>

09:49.414 --> 09:50.654
- Craig just went in the oil.

09:55.879 --> 09:57.545
<i>- I grab a file to check and see</i>

09:57.589 --> 09:59.172
<i>if the blade steel hardened.</i>

09:59.216 --> 10:00.715
Boy, I'm still getting
file bite on this.

10:00.759 --> 10:02.467
This ain't good.

10:02.511 --> 10:04.719
<i>The file teeth start biting
in my blade.</i>

10:04.763 --> 10:06.513
I know this blade isn't hard.

10:06.556 --> 10:08.473
<i>Well,
I'm gonna have to re-quench it.</i>

10:08.517 --> 10:10.809
I can warp it
or crack it very easily here.

10:10.852 --> 10:12.644
<i>If I don't get this right,</i>

10:12.687 --> 10:15.730
<i>everything I've done up
to this point means nothing.</i>

10:15.774 --> 10:17.315
- He goes in again.

10:24.241 --> 10:26.741
<i>[rock music]</i>

10:26.785 --> 10:28.243
- This ain't good.

10:28.286 --> 10:30.245
I know this blade isn't hard.

10:30.288 --> 10:31.955
<i>I'm gonna have to re-quench it.</i>

10:31.998 --> 10:34.123
<i>I can warp it
or crack it very easily here.</i>

10:34.167 --> 10:37.961
- He goes in again.

10:38.004 --> 10:41.965
- It went nice and straight
into the oil.

10:42.008 --> 10:45.093
- Hoo, I got her hard that time.

10:45.136 --> 10:47.929
- Look at Jeffrey's
marking his blade here.

10:47.973 --> 10:49.848
<i>- I know I'm gonna
have to put a handle on.</i>

10:49.891 --> 10:51.851
I'm marking the holes
in my blade

10:51.893 --> 10:54.936
so I can drill them
before I quench.

10:54.980 --> 10:56.896
- It's a good move.

10:56.940 --> 10:58.898
<i>- After you quench,
it's gonna be way too hard</i>

10:58.942 --> 11:00.608
to drill through
most of the time.

11:00.652 --> 11:03.903
- Bladesmiths, you have
30 minutes remaining.

11:03.947 --> 11:06.447
<i>[rock music]</i>

11:06.491 --> 11:08.283
- Kim looks like she just
wants to take that blade

11:08.326 --> 11:10.326
and chuck it against the wall.

11:10.370 --> 11:13.246
- I'm in a race
just to complete a piece

11:13.290 --> 11:15.790
to turn in to the judges.

11:15.834 --> 11:17.125
- Kim 's over to the grinder.

11:17.168 --> 11:19.085
- All right,
thank goodness for that.

11:19.129 --> 11:22.463
She can't afford
to waste any time.

11:22.507 --> 11:24.799
- I've never made a blade
in just three hours,

11:24.843 --> 11:26.718
so this is, like,
testing everything,

11:26.761 --> 11:29.387
where normally I have a lot
of time to make decisions.

11:29.431 --> 11:32.974
- She needs to take
a deep breath and move forward.

11:33.018 --> 11:34.976
- I like how Harry's
dipping his finger into the oil

11:35.020 --> 11:36.769
to check the temperature.

11:36.813 --> 11:38.773
<i>- Heat treating is so important,</i>

11:38.815 --> 11:41.357
because you can have the most
beautiful knife in the world,

11:41.401 --> 11:43.526
but if the heat
treat's not right on it,

11:43.570 --> 11:44.861
the knife is useless.

11:44.905 --> 11:46.529
Quenching.

11:46.573 --> 11:48.364
- So Harry's in the oil.
What did you think, J.?

11:48.408 --> 11:50.116
- I thought
it was still a little cool.

11:50.160 --> 11:52.493
I wasn't really happy
with the color of that blade.

11:52.537 --> 11:54.913
I would really like to see
Harry do a second quench.

11:54.956 --> 11:57.665
- As would I.

11:57.709 --> 12:02.462
- Bladesmiths,
you have five minutes remaining.

12:02.505 --> 12:03.838
- Oh, my goodness.
- That's gonna...

12:03.882 --> 12:05.256
That's gonna be very, very hot.

12:05.300 --> 12:06.507
Holy cow...
- Holy crap.

12:06.551 --> 12:07.508
Drop it, drop it, drop it...

