- Drop it in there...
- Drop it in.

12:09.888 --> 12:11.054
Let go of it. Let go of it.

12:11.097 --> 12:12.847
- I'm leaning back.
- Whoo!

12:12.891 --> 12:14.390
- Whoo!

12:14.434 --> 12:18.353
- Ten! Nine! Eight! Seven!

12:18.396 --> 12:22.190
Six! Five! Four! Three!

12:22.233 --> 12:24.192
Two! One!

12:24.235 --> 12:26.903
Bladesmiths, stop your work!

12:26.947 --> 12:30.573
Please return to your anvils.

12:30.617 --> 12:33.326
<i>- I'm thinking, "Whoa,
Jeff, Harry, and Craig,</i>

12:33.370 --> 12:38.539
they definitely got a lot more
work done than I did."

12:38.583 --> 12:40.500
- Bladesmiths,
when you came here today,

12:40.543 --> 12:42.710
you were asked to forge a blade
of your own design

12:42.754 --> 12:44.212
in your signature style

12:44.255 --> 12:46.297
from one of these pieces
of scrap metal.

12:46.341 --> 12:49.384
You've each finished
a blade in three hours.

12:49.427 --> 12:51.552
Good job.

12:51.596 --> 12:54.764
Craig, please present
your blade to our judges.

12:54.808 --> 12:56.724
J?

12:56.768 --> 12:58.768
<i>- You got a little bit of curve
in the tang here,</i>

12:58.812 --> 13:01.771
<i>but that's pretty easy to fix.</i>

13:01.815 --> 13:03.481
I like the sweep of it.
Good job on that.

13:03.525 --> 13:05.984
- Thank you, thank you.
- Doug?

13:06.027 --> 13:07.360
- I love your design here.

13:07.404 --> 13:09.404
Definitely,
with the flaring there,

13:09.447 --> 13:12.824
it lends itself to be
a good chopper.

13:12.867 --> 13:14.492
Very nice.
- Thank you.

13:14.536 --> 13:17.745
- Harry, please present
your work.

13:17.789 --> 13:20.081
<i>- A lot of meat in the handle,
so there's still a ways</i>

13:20.125 --> 13:22.250
<i>to go
to get this down to weight.</i>

13:22.293 --> 13:23.751
<i>Just a bit concerned</i>

13:23.795 --> 13:26.963
if that heat treat
really hardened her up.

13:27.007 --> 13:28.589
- What do you think, Doug?

13:28.633 --> 13:30.466
- Nice design for a chopper,
Harry.

13:30.510 --> 13:32.635
<i>And there's nothing wrong
with rough around the edges.</i>

13:32.679 --> 13:34.303
It looks like it's gonna
function well.

13:34.347 --> 13:36.180
Good feel.
- Thank you.

13:36.224 --> 13:39.100
- Kim, please present
your blade.

13:39.144 --> 13:41.269
<i>- Well, it's a nice design
for cutting and chopping.</i>

13:41.312 --> 13:43.938
<i>It definitely has got
some rough aspects.</i>

13:43.982 --> 13:45.481
Got some wiggle in there.

13:45.525 --> 13:47.150
But it's still doable,
still workable.

13:47.193 --> 13:49.152
Thank you.
- Dave?

13:49.195 --> 13:51.529
- Well,
I loved your original design.

13:51.573 --> 13:53.948
Now, you didn't quite
draw this metal out far enough.

13:53.992 --> 13:56.117
But you definitely
started over again from stretch,

13:56.161 --> 13:58.286
and it's commendable that you
were able to turn a weapon

13:58.329 --> 13:59.537
in at all.

13:59.581 --> 14:00.830
- Thanks.

14:00.874 --> 14:05.668
- Jeff, please present
your blade.

14:05.712 --> 14:07.128
- It's got a nice shape.

14:07.172 --> 14:08.463
It's got a good feel
to it overall.

14:08.506 --> 14:10.465
Very good.

14:10.508 --> 14:12.633
- There's a lot of weight still
on the head of that blade.

14:12.677 --> 14:13.968
I mean, it'll help in the chop,

14:14.012 --> 14:15.344
but at the same time,
the second part

14:15.388 --> 14:17.013
of the challenge is a rope cut.

14:17.057 --> 14:20.516
Too much weight in that head
might set you back.

14:20.560 --> 14:22.060
- Well, bladesmiths,

14:22.103 --> 14:24.187
this will be a difficult
decision for our judges.

14:24.230 --> 14:26.439
Thank you.

14:26.483 --> 14:29.484
<i>[tense music]</i>

14:29.527 --> 14:31.152
- All right.
- That was a good time, man.

14:31.196 --> 14:33.529
- That was good. That was fun.
- That was a good time.

14:33.573 --> 14:35.156
- Nerve-racking.

14:35.200 --> 14:37.160
- All right, guys,
let's start with Craig's blade.

14:37.202 --> 14:39.160
How did he do overall, Doug?

14:39.204 --> 14:41.204
<i>- Well, the handle construction
I love.</i>

14:41.247 --> 14:43.164
<i>You can choke up
if you want control</i>

14:43.208 --> 14:46.417
or the length of that for
when you're doing the ice chop.

14:46.461 --> 14:48.878
Overall finish is beautiful.

14:48.922 --> 14:50.588
- Dave, what do you think?

14:50.632 --> 14:53.508
- Well, the way he
tapered the tang on the handle,

14:53.551 --> 14:55.551
you know, took all
that weight out here.

14:55.595 --> 14:59.722
I mean, it already
feels like a beautiful knife.

14:59.766 --> 15:01.182
- I hope the steel
was what I think it is

15:01.226 --> 15:03.101
and it holds up in heat treat.

15:03.144 --> 15:04.685
It's tough
when you don't know what it is.

15:04.729 --> 15:06.529
I mean, it could... anything can
happen there.

15:06.564 --> 15:08.147
- My heat treat
is my biggest fear.

15:08.191 --> 15:13.277
- All right, let's move
on to Harry's blade.

15:13.321 --> 15:16.197
<i>- It's got a good shape, but I
think the biggest issue is</i>

15:16.241 --> 15:18.741
whether or not this blade
is hardened enough.

15:18.785 --> 15:21.077
- Can we test that please?
- Oh, yeah.

15:21.121 --> 15:22.620
You can do a file check.

15:22.664 --> 15:24.372
If the steel's hard enough,

15:24.415 --> 15:26.707
the file won't even bite
into the edge of the blade.

15:26.751 --> 15:30.878
Ooh, how it's stopping...

15:30.922 --> 15:33.548
even the sound's saying
it's digging in.

15:33.591 --> 15:37.009
It's not properly hardened.

15:37.053 --> 15:38.511
- Okay, let's talk
about Kim's blade.

15:38.555 --> 15:40.930
<i>[tense music]</i>

15:40.974 --> 15:45.059
<i>- There is severe arc
in the tang.</i>

15:45.103 --> 15:48.062
She's got a lot
of grinding to do.

15:48.106 --> 15:50.106
- Oh, I'm definitely wondering
what they're saying.

15:50.150 --> 15:54.277
- Well, it is from her signature
style being a kitchen tool,

15:54.320 --> 15:56.779
and kitchen tools
are known to be chopping.

15:56.823 --> 15:58.781
The big question is, is this
the kind of kitchen tool

15:58.825 --> 16:02.451
that's gonna stand up to an ice
chop and then a rope cut?

16:02.495 --> 16:05.454
- All right, let's move
on to Jeff's blade there.

16:05.498 --> 16:07.248
<i>- A lot of work left to do.</i>

16:07.292 --> 16:09.542
<i>This pin hole,
it's really poorly placed.</i>

16:09.586 --> 16:11.919
<i>I mean, this is the junction
between the blade</i>

16:11.963 --> 16:13.171
and the handle right there,

16:13.214 --> 16:15.089
and that structural flaw
concerns me

16:15.133 --> 16:16.966
if this is gonna hold up
during a chop test.

16:17.010 --> 16:20.428
We've seen
that ice eat blades alive.

16:20.471 --> 16:23.097
- Dave?
- I'm with J. 100%.

16:23.141 --> 16:24.932
<i>Putting that hole right there,</i>

16:24.976 --> 16:26.976
it's almost building in
a failure point.

16:27.020 --> 16:29.812
<i>[tense music]</i>

16:29.856 --> 16:34.150
- Judges, is there one
of these blades

16:34.194 --> 16:37.528
that did not meet the parameters
of the challenge?

16:37.572 --> 16:38.863
- Yes.
- Yes.

16:38.907 --> 16:40.573
- Yes.

16:40.617 --> 16:42.617
- All right, judges,
let's go tell our bladesmiths.

16:42.660 --> 16:44.994
<i>[tense music]</i>

16:45.038 --> 16:48.915
Well, bladesmiths,
the decision has been made.

16:48.958 --> 16:50.666
¶ ¶

16:50.710 --> 16:53.836
And now it's time for one
of you to leave the Forge.

16:53.880 --> 16:57.298
¶ ¶

16:57.342 --> 16:59.926
Harry...

16:59.969 --> 17:02.970
your blade did not make the cut.

17:03.014 --> 17:05.139
- Harry, I know you thought
that metal was pretty hard,

17:05.183 --> 17:08.434
so you kind of hedged
your bets on the quench.

17:08.478 --> 17:10.978
<i>Well, we did a file test
on that knife,</i>

17:11.022 --> 17:15.107
<i>and that edge just isn't hard
enough to go forward.</i>

17:15.151 --> 17:16.609
Having said that, though,

17:16.653 --> 17:19.320
it was such a pleasure
to watch you work.

17:19.364 --> 17:20.988
Your energy was infectious.

17:21.032 --> 17:23.991
I mean, it literally spread
to all the other smiths.

17:24.035 --> 17:26.160
I just wish you'd gotten
that metal hot enough

17:26.204 --> 17:27.995
that it could've gone forward.

17:28.039 --> 17:29.664
But thank you, sir.

17:29.707 --> 17:31.249
- Thank you.

17:31.292 --> 17:33.542
- Harry, it's time
to surrender your weapon.

17:33.586 --> 17:36.504
<i>[tense music]</i>

17:36.547 --> 17:38.172
<i>- I'm a little disappointed,</i>

17:38.216 --> 17:42.009
but that's the way
things go in knife-making.

17:42.053 --> 17:44.637
<i>I came here to represent
me and my brother.</i>

17:44.681 --> 17:46.847
<i>He's not physically able
to compete in a challenge</i>

17:46.891 --> 17:50.726
like this, so I did the best
that I could to represent me

17:50.770 --> 17:52.395
<i>and him both.</i>

17:52.438 --> 17:54.939
<i>I hope that my brother
will be proud of me.</i>

17:54.983 --> 17:56.983
<i>[tense music]</i>

17:57.026 --> 17:59.235
- Welcome back to the Forge,
bladesmiths.

17:59.279 --> 18:01.404
In this round,
you will turn your blades

18:01.447 --> 18:05.199
into fully functioning weapons
by attaching a handle to them

18:05.243 --> 18:07.910
using the range
of materials provided to you.

18:07.954 --> 18:10.538
You have three hours
to complete this challenge.

18:10.581 --> 18:13.165
You can also use this time
to address any flaws or issues

18:13.209 --> 18:17.211
that the judges identified
with your blades earlier.

18:17.255 --> 18:18.879
After the three hours is up,

18:18.923 --> 18:23.592
we will test your blades
in an ice chop

18:23.636 --> 18:25.970
and a rope slice.

18:26.014 --> 18:28.306
Remember, after this round,

18:28.349 --> 18:31.058
one of you will have
to surrender your weapon

18:31.102 --> 18:32.518
and leave the Forge.

18:32.562 --> 18:33.853
<i>[tense music]</i>

18:33.896 --> 18:35.104
Good luck, bladesmiths.

18:35.148 --> 18:37.315
Your time starts now.

18:37.358 --> 18:40.568
<i>[rock music]</i>

18:40.611 --> 18:43.237
<i>- There's a small bend
in my tang,</i>

18:43.281 --> 18:46.365
so I straightaway just start
working on getting it flat.

18:46.409 --> 18:49.618
- What is she gonna have to do
to advance into the next round?

18:49.662 --> 18:51.746
- Personally, I 'd like
to see her lose the tang,

18:51.789 --> 18:53.748
or most of it... shave it down.

18:53.791 --> 18:55.958
- I almost feel
like you could get two hands

18:56.002 --> 18:57.752
on her tang right now.

18:57.795 --> 19:01.088
- I was thinking about the chop
and the rope cut.

19:01.132 --> 19:02.965
<i>It just didn't make sense
to have such a long tang</i>

19:03.009 --> 19:04.800
<i>on that knife.</i>

19:04.844 --> 19:06.344
- And there it goes.

19:06.387 --> 19:09.722
<i>[rock music]</i>

19:09.766 --> 19:11.932
<i>- I have a little bit
of a wobble in the blade.</i>

19:11.976 --> 19:14.769
<i>It kicks off to one side
just a little bit.</i>

19:14.812 --> 19:16.604
<i>So I want to get
that straightened up</i>

19:16.647 --> 19:18.439
<i>and get everything centered,</i>

19:18.483 --> 19:20.608
<i>so I've got a nice
symmetric blade.</i>

19:20.651 --> 19:24.362
<i>So the challenge is to chop a
block of ice and chop a rope.</i>

19:24.405 --> 19:26.280
¶ ¶

19:26.324 --> 19:28.284
<i>That bend, it creates more drag.</i>

19:28.326 --> 19:30.910
<i>So it could not cut the rope
if it's got that bend.</i>

19:30.953 --> 19:33.954
If I don't get this bend
out of mg blade, I'm screwed.

19:33.998 --> 19:35.289
¶ ¶

19:35.333 --> 19:38.084
<i>- I cut the two pieces
of micarta</i>

19:38.127 --> 19:40.461
to go on each side of the tang.

19:40.505 --> 19:44.799
I epoxy it with the pins, ,
and then I refine the shape

19:44.842 --> 19:47.593
until I meet up
with the metal and the tang.

19:47.637 --> 19:52.139
<i>I'm not a huge fan
of shiny, slippery handles.</i>

19:52.183 --> 19:53.891
The color of that micarta...

19:53.935 --> 19:56.477
It was a dark brown
with a little cherry in there...

19:56.521 --> 20:00.272
<i>I think it made my knife
have a classic edge to it.</i>

20:00.316 --> 20:02.024
¶ ¶

20:02.068 --> 20:03.609
- Bladesmiths...

20:03.653 --> 20:07.196
you have 90 minutes remaining.

20:07.240 --> 20:12.368
¶ ¶

20:12.412 --> 20:16.038
- I start to put my pins
down in my wood on one side

20:16.082 --> 20:17.998
and put my blade on top of it,

20:18.042 --> 20:22.169
<i>and they're starting
to not meet up correctly.</i>

20:22.213 --> 20:25.172
<i>I'm thinking,
"Just do it quickly."</i>

20:25.216 --> 20:27.007
- All right,
Kim is in panic mode.

20:27.051 --> 20:29.093
She needs to relax.

20:29.137 --> 20:31.345
If she keeps trying to force it,
she's got a good chance

20:31.389 --> 20:33.556
of breaking that handle material
and fracturing it.

20:33.599 --> 20:35.433
And Kim 's already
started over once.

20:35.476 --> 20:38.352
I don't think she wants
to do it a second time.

20:38.396 --> 20:39.895
- [bleep].

20:46.654 --> 20:49.280
<i>- The wood pieces for my handle
and my tang,</i>

20:49.323 --> 20:51.240
they're starting
to not meet up correctly.

20:51.284 --> 20:53.451
- If she keeps trying to force
it, she's got a good chance

20:53.494 --> 20:56.787
of breaking that handle material
and fracturing it.

20:56.831 --> 20:59.457
<i>[tense music]</i>

20:59.500 --> 21:02.251
- This is, like,
the worst job in history.

21:02.295 --> 21:04.420
That wood, if it's not
completely connected

21:04.464 --> 21:06.255
<i>with the tang, I mean,
it could fly off.</i>

21:06.299 --> 21:08.757
<i>So I put some extra glue
in there,</i>

21:08.801 --> 21:11.427
just to make sure it would
hold up to their tests.

21:11.471 --> 21:13.429
- How's it coming along?

21:13.473 --> 21:15.181
- Heh heh. I think it's okay.
- Good, good.

21:15.224 --> 21:16.807
- Yeah.

21:16.851 --> 21:18.434
<i>- Standing
at the handle material rack,</i>

21:18.478 --> 21:20.102
<i>I see this green
and black kirinite.</i>

21:20.146 --> 21:22.104
I'm stoked.

21:22.148 --> 21:23.898
<i>It's a real nice material.</i>

21:23.941 --> 21:25.983
I know it's gonna be perfect
for the zombie apocalypse

21:26.027 --> 21:28.486
<i>my son reads
all about all the time.</i>

21:28.529 --> 21:30.237
<i>I'm shaping my handle,</i>

21:30.281 --> 21:32.448
and then I start rolling
the edges over on the handle

21:32.492 --> 21:33.782
to make it nice and smooth.

21:33.826 --> 21:36.785
<i>[rock music]</i>

21:36.829 --> 21:39.330
<i>I'm shaping. I'm grinding.
I'm rounding.</i>

21:39.373 --> 21:40.956
It's just total chaos.

21:41.000 --> 21:43.083
<i>If I get my material too hot,</i>

21:43.127 --> 21:46.295
I can actually ruin it and peel
it off and cause it to buckle

21:46.339 --> 21:48.797
<i>and actually try
to rip away from the tang.</i>

21:48.841 --> 21:51.675
That would be a huge setback
and cost me everything.

21:51.719 --> 21:53.427
<i>I could go home.</i>

21:53.471 --> 21:57.014
<i>[rock music]</i>

21:57.058 --> 21:59.016
- During the sharpening process,

21:59.060 --> 22:01.477
I was just experimenting
with the different stones.

22:01.521 --> 22:05.523
- Jeffrey's on a pretty
aggressive stone right there.

22:05.566 --> 22:07.983
<i>- They were a little small,
a little narrow.</i>

22:08.027 --> 22:09.818
I wasn't having much luck.

22:09.862 --> 22:12.321
I really had to do sections
of the blade.

22:12.365 --> 22:13.697
I didn't like that.

22:13.741 --> 22:15.741
- It seems like a lot of work.

22:15.785 --> 22:17.409
- That's why I like
sharpening on belts.

22:17.453 --> 22:20.913
It takes, like, two minutes.

22:20.957 --> 22:25.042
- Ten, nine, eight, seven,

22:25.086 --> 22:28.045
six, five, four,

22:28.089 --> 22:30.965
three, two, one.

22:31.008 --> 22:32.383
Stop working.

22:32.426 --> 22:35.928
<i>[tense music]</i>

22:35.972 --> 22:38.430
- And we all kind of made
a different style of knife,

22:38.474 --> 22:40.391
so it's gonna be interesting
to see how everything

22:40.434 --> 22:44.520
stacks up in the test.

22:44.564 --> 22:46.772
- Bladesmiths,
we're at the ice chop now.

22:46.816 --> 22:49.108
<i>It's gonna test the strength
and durability of the blades</i>

22:49.151 --> 22:50.609
that you've forged
and heat treated.

22:50.653 --> 22:52.736
I'm gonna take
each of your blades

22:52.780 --> 22:56.532
and do seven vertical
chops into the ice.

22:56.576 --> 22:58.367
Craig, you already
got a big smile on your face.

22:58.411 --> 23:00.494
You ready to go?
- I'm ready to do it, yeah.

23:00.538 --> 23:02.037
<i>[tense music]</i>

23:02.081 --> 23:03.706
<i>- Let's have some fun.
- All right.</i>

23:03.749 --> 23:05.249
<i>I'm feeling a little nervous.</i>

23:05.293 --> 23:07.042
<i>I just don't want that edge
to roll.</i>

23:07.086 --> 23:09.566
I want to see nice, clean cuts,
see it hold up and perform.

23:11.507 --> 23:19.471
<i>[rock music]</i>

23:19.515 --> 23:20.723
¶ ¶

23:20.766 --> 23:24.059
- Wow.
- Nice.

23:24.103 --> 23:27.938
- Edge stayed true, no chipping,
nothing bent.

23:27.982 --> 23:29.565
It's a good grip.

23:29.609 --> 23:31.775
It did roll just a little bit.
- Did it? Yeah.

23:31.819 --> 23:33.611
- But it took a good chunk
of ice out of there.

23:33.654 --> 23:35.070
Nice job.
- Good deal, good deal.

23:35.114 --> 23:37.114
Thank you.
- Kim, you ready?

23:37.158 --> 23:38.949
- I'm ready.

23:38.993 --> 23:41.368
<i>- Okay, let's chop some ice.</i>

23:41.412 --> 23:43.287
<i>- I'm a little nervous
about my handle.</i>

23:43.331 --> 23:45.539
It could have potential
to maybe fly out of your hands.

23:45.583 --> 23:47.124
<i>There's nothing really there
to, like,</i>

23:47.168 --> 23:48.917
<i>contour it to your hand.</i>

23:48.961 --> 23:50.919
<i>But we'll see if it holds up.</i>

23:50.963 --> 23:53.922
<i>[rock music]</i>

23:53.966 --> 23:57.843
¶ ¶

23:57.887 --> 24:00.638
Sweet.

24:00.681 --> 24:02.306
- Your blade held up well.

24:02.350 --> 24:04.433
You've got that heavy convex
edge that supported it.

24:04.477 --> 24:09.563
It split the ice quite well,
though not down as far as Craig.

24:09.607 --> 24:11.440
- Oh.

24:11.484 --> 24:15.110
- The handle... the handle
had a tendency to roll,

24:15.154 --> 24:16.945
especially on that last swing.

24:16.989 --> 24:19.948
It kind of glanced off,
but good job on the blade.

24:19.992 --> 24:21.659
- Thanks.

24:21.702 --> 24:24.244
<i>- Jeff, you ready to go?
Ready to have some fun?</i>

24:24.288 --> 24:25.968
- Oh, yeah.
- Okay.

24:25.998 --> 24:27.873
- I feel like my edge
is very sharp.

24:27.917 --> 24:30.626
<i>I'm only worried about it
being a little too thin</i>

24:30.670 --> 24:32.920
<i>and going through the ice.</i>

24:32.963 --> 24:35.923
<i>[rock music]</i>

24:35.966 --> 24:40.260
¶ ¶

24:40.304 --> 24:43.472
- Well, Jeff,
a very thin handle,

24:43.516 --> 24:46.350
a little harder to hold onto it
with those swings.

24:46.394 --> 24:50.521
But it stayed straight,
and it chopped some ice.

24:50.564 --> 24:52.731
Nicely done.
- Thank you, sir.

24:52.775 --> 24:54.858
- All right, smiths,
each of your blades

24:54.902 --> 24:58.320
is gonna get three attempts
to slice through this rope.

24:58.364 --> 25:01.824
This sharpness test is going
to see how well your edges

25:01.867 --> 25:04.827
held up after chopping ice.

25:04.870 --> 25:06.370
Craig, again, you're up first.

25:06.414 --> 25:07.705
- I'm ready.

25:07.748 --> 25:10.708
<i>[rock music]</i>

25:10.751 --> 25:14.128
¶ ¶

25:14.171 --> 25:15.838
- Oh!

25:15.881 --> 25:18.006
<i>[tense music]</i>

25:18.050 --> 25:20.634
<i>It left a few strands
of the rope together.</i>

25:20.678 --> 25:22.636
I would've liked to see it
take it all down, though.

25:22.680 --> 25:26.515
- Got the toothy edge
that bites into the fibers,

25:26.559 --> 25:28.392
and there was enough blade
to drag through.

25:28.436 --> 25:30.144
I mean,
it took out most of this rope.

25:30.187 --> 25:31.562
- Yup.
- Almost there.

25:31.605 --> 25:34.857
- I know it. I know it.
- So close. Nice job.

25:34.900 --> 25:36.358
- Thank you, thank you.

25:36.402 --> 25:38.360
- Kim, you're up next.

25:38.404 --> 25:39.945
<i>- Watching Craig 's knife</i>

25:39.989 --> 25:42.072
<i>not make it all the way
through the rope,</i>

25:42.116 --> 25:44.241
it's pretty surprising to me.

25:44.285 --> 25:46.243
His blades
looked really super sharp,

25:46.287 --> 25:49.413
and I'm pretty worried
about my chances.

25:50.666 --> 25:53.625
<i>[rock music]</i>

25:53.669 --> 25:57.629
¶ ¶

25:57.673 --> 26:00.883
- Got it?
Awesome.

26:00.926 --> 26:02.676
- Kim, I've got to say,

26:02.720 --> 26:06.388
there's no edge up here
on this part of your blade.

26:06.432 --> 26:08.223
But right down here there is,

26:08.267 --> 26:10.058
and that's
what bit into the rope.

26:10.102 --> 26:11.393
But good job.

26:11.437 --> 26:12.686
- Thanks.

26:12.730 --> 26:14.021
- Jeff, you're up next.

26:14.064 --> 26:16.023
- I can't wait.

26:16.066 --> 26:19.026
<i>[rock music]</i>

26:19.069 --> 26:21.779
¶ ¶

26:21.822 --> 26:24.490
- Oof.
- Good job.

26:24.533 --> 26:26.575
- Two swings, Jeff.

26:26.619 --> 26:27.951
Very nice.

26:27.995 --> 26:29.912
It had good weight to it.

26:29.955 --> 26:31.246
Good job.

26:31.290 --> 26:32.498
- Thank you.

26:32.541 --> 26:35.042
<i>[tense music]</i>

26:35.085 --> 26:38.462
- Bladesmiths,
after careful deliberation,

26:38.506 --> 26:41.423
the judges have decided
which two of you

26:41.467 --> 26:44.927
will move forward into
the "Forged in Fire" final

26:44.970 --> 26:47.304
and which of you
must be eliminated.

26:47.348 --> 26:50.349
¶ ¶

26:50.392 --> 26:52.476
The person leaving
the Forge is...

26:52.520 --> 26:54.269
¶ ¶

26:59.860 --> 27:02.486
<i>[tense music]</i>

27:02.530 --> 27:05.572
- Bladesmiths,
the judges have decided

27:05.616 --> 27:08.242
which of you must be eliminated.

27:08.285 --> 27:12.621
¶ ¶

27:12.665 --> 27:17.876
Kim, your weapon
did not make the cut.

27:17.920 --> 27:20.045
¶ ¶

27:20.089 --> 27:21.839
- Well, Kim, your knife
didn't do quite as well

27:21.882 --> 27:23.382
as some in the ice chop

27:23.425 --> 27:25.384
and did better than some
in the rope test.

27:25.427 --> 27:27.261
So that kind
of balanced things out.

27:27.304 --> 27:29.680
From there, we had to look
at your finished product,

27:29.723 --> 27:31.765
<i>and there was a bunch of issues
on that blade.</i>

27:31.809 --> 27:33.767
<i>I mean, there's waves
in the blade.</i>

27:33.811 --> 27:36.854
<i>And the handle itself really
wasn't conducive for the tests.</i>

27:36.897 --> 27:38.522
<i>It was very hard to hold onto.</i>

27:38.566 --> 27:40.482
<i>It took a lot of concentration
to not have it</i>

27:40.526 --> 27:42.484
veer left and right.

27:42.528 --> 27:44.528
And there's just issues
that we couldn't look past.

27:44.572 --> 27:46.363
¶ ¶

27:46.407 --> 27:49.283
- Kim, please surrender
your weapon.

27:49.326 --> 27:50.784
<i>[rock music]</i>

27:50.828 --> 27:52.202
- Thank you, guys.
It's been fun.

27:52.246 --> 27:53.704
- Thank you very much.

27:53.747 --> 27:55.914
- I feel like I've proven
a lot to myself.

27:55.958 --> 27:57.666
See ya, guys.

27:57.710 --> 27:59.668
Now, I mean,
I've passed a chop test,

27:59.712 --> 28:01.503
and I've passed a rope cut.

28:01.547 --> 28:03.547
So I'm pretty excited
where I am.

28:03.591 --> 28:06.300
J's feedback was not a shock
to me at all.

28:06.343 --> 28:09.553
With that handle,
it was pretty ridiculous.

28:09.597 --> 28:12.598
So that's why I'm going home.

28:15.102 --> 28:16.560
<i>[tense music]</i>

28:16.604 --> 28:20.022
- Jeff, Craig, congratulations.

28:20.065 --> 28:22.524
You've both made it through
to the "Forged in Fire" final,

28:22.568 --> 28:27.362
and you're both one step closer
to a check for $10,000.

28:27.406 --> 28:29.323
In the first two rounds
of competition,

28:29.366 --> 28:31.700
you forged a weapon
in your signature style.

28:31.744 --> 28:34.453
Now we're sending you back
to your home forges,

28:34.496 --> 28:38.790
where you will forge
an iconic weapon from history,

28:38.834 --> 28:40.417
the war hammer.

28:40.461 --> 28:42.544
- Nice.

28:42.588 --> 28:44.713
<i>- A war hammer
is a medieval weapon</i>

28:44.757 --> 28:46.715
<i>developed in the 14th century</i>

28:46.759 --> 28:48.425
<i>that came about primarily
as a response</i>

28:48.469 --> 28:51.011
<i>to advanced armor technology.</i>

28:51.055 --> 28:53.430
<i>By this time, the armorists
had created suits</i>

28:53.474 --> 28:56.433
<i>of plate armor
that were so hard and smooth</i>

28:56.477 --> 28:58.518
<i>that swords
would bounce off them.</i>

28:58.562 --> 29:01.229
<i>The war hammer could deliver
its full force to the target</i>

29:01.273 --> 29:04.733
<i>and do serious damage without
having to penetrate the armor.</i>

29:04.777 --> 29:07.694
<i>Its steel head with a spike
on one side had a handle</i>

29:07.738 --> 29:11.073
<i>that varied in length but was
generally just long enough</i>

29:11.116 --> 29:13.200
<i>to be wielded with one hand.</i>

29:13.243 --> 29:16.244
<i>The spiked end could be used
for hooking the target's legs,</i>

29:16.288 --> 29:18.080
<i>reins, or shield,</i>

29:18.123 --> 29:20.457
<i>or used
as an armor-piercing device.</i>

29:20.501 --> 29:23.126
<i>As the use
of body armor declined,</i>

29:23.170 --> 29:24.670
<i>so did the need
for the war hammer.</i>

29:24.713 --> 29:26.922
<i>However, it can still
be seen today</i>

29:26.966 --> 29:29.424
<i>in the popular film
trilogy "The Hobbit"</i>

29:29.468 --> 29:33.720
<i>and has lent its name
to board game Warhammer.</i>

29:33.764 --> 29:36.390
Your challenge is to forge
a war hammer.

29:36.433 --> 29:38.266
It must be an authentic,

29:38.310 --> 29:41.812
fully functioning version
of that late-medieval weapon.

29:41.855 --> 29:43.647
<i>- I feel a little bit
confident on it.</i>

29:43.691 --> 29:45.451
<i>It's a weapon
I'm a little bit familiar with,</i>

29:45.484 --> 29:47.776
Plus, I use a hammer
on a daily basis.

29:47.820 --> 29:50.278
- The weapon parameters
are as follows.

29:50.322 --> 29:54.616
The length of the head
must be at least 2 1/2 inches,

29:54.660 --> 29:58.453
and the length of the pike must
be at least 3 inches in length.

29:58.497 --> 30:00.122
- I've never made a war hammer,

30:00.165 --> 30:03.625
<i>but I've made some hatchets
and tomahawks.</i>

30:03.669 --> 30:06.586
- So you will have five days
to complete this challenge.

30:06.630 --> 30:08.797
When the five days is up,
you will return

30:08.841 --> 30:12.050
and present your war hammers
to our panel of judges.

30:12.094 --> 30:13.635
They will submit those weapons

30:13.679 --> 30:16.972
<i>to a series of dynamic
and rigorous tests.</i>

30:17.016 --> 30:18.849
When the testing is complete,

30:18.892 --> 30:22.060
they will decide which of you
is the "Forged in Fire" champion

30:22.104 --> 30:24.521
and walks away with $10,000.

30:24.565 --> 30:26.398
Good luck, bladesmiths.

30:26.442 --> 30:29.109
We'll see you in five days.

30:29.153 --> 30:33.030
<i>[rock music]</i>

30:33.073 --> 30:34.990
<i>- Today is day one.</i>

30:35.034 --> 30:37.492
<i>I'm excited to get this thing
done in my home forge.</i>

30:37.536 --> 30:38.827
It's a lot more comfortable
here.

30:38.871 --> 30:40.412
I know my tools.

30:40.456 --> 30:42.164
<i>I want to do a ram's head</i>

30:42.207 --> 30:45.333
<i>with horns following the sides
of the hammer.</i>

30:45.377 --> 30:48.003
<i>I think I can knock it out.</i>

30:48.047 --> 30:50.672
<i>[rock music]</i>

30:50.716 --> 30:53.341
<i>I'm gonna use
a tool-steel ball bearing</i>

30:53.385 --> 30:56.011
<i>as the head of my hammer,</i>

30:56.055 --> 31:00.640
<i>make sure it's a solid block
of steel by the time I'm done.</i>

31:00.684 --> 31:03.143
<i>I'm about to punch a hole
through the head of the hammer</i>

31:03.187 --> 31:04.394
<i>for the handle.</i>

31:04.438 --> 31:05.896
Hopefully, nothing goes wrong.

31:05.939 --> 31:08.607
<i>I could split the hammer in two.</i>

31:08.650 --> 31:10.942
Then I would have
to start from square one.

31:10.986 --> 31:13.945
<i>[rock music]</i>

31:13.989 --> 31:15.989
¶ ¶

31:18.160 --> 31:20.202
¶ ¶

31:20.245 --> 31:22.245
<i>- I'm happy to be here
at the home forge.</i>

31:22.289 --> 31:24.706
<i>I'm in my element.
I know what all my tools are.</i>

31:24.750 --> 31:26.374
<i>I know how to use my tools.</i>

31:26.418 --> 31:30.879
<i>So being here at home's
a big advantage for me.</i>

31:30.923 --> 31:33.048
It takes a lot of steel
to make the amount of Damascus

31:33.092 --> 31:35.550
that I'm gonna make.

31:35.594 --> 31:38.386
<i>The plan for the day
is to get my Damascus made.</i>

31:38.430 --> 31:40.430
<i>I'm gonna
take the two dissimilar metals.</i>

31:40.474 --> 31:42.724
<i>I'm gonna heat 'em up in my
forge, get everything hot.</i>

31:42.768 --> 31:44.518
<i>I'm gonna flux 'em,</i>

31:44.561 --> 31:47.312
keep the oxygen out of there
so scales doesn't form.

31:47.356 --> 31:49.314
Then I'm gonna
beat 'em together.

31:49.358 --> 31:52.317
<i>[frenetic rock music]</i>

31:52.361 --> 31:54.402
¶ ¶

31:54.446 --> 31:56.696
<i>I'm feeling a little nervous
right now making this Damascus.</i>

31:56.740 --> 31:58.657
<i>I can get a bad weld.</i>

31:58.700 --> 32:00.242
<i>If I get a bad weld in it,</i>

32:00.285 --> 32:02.244
everything
I've done so far is ruined.

32:02.287 --> 32:04.412
<i>It's not a serviceable weapon
at that point.</i>

32:04.456 --> 32:06.915
<i>I'd have to scrap it
and start again.</i>

32:06.959 --> 32:08.625
<i>[rock music]</i>

32:08.669 --> 32:10.710
<i>- I'm halfway through day two,</i>

32:10.754 --> 32:13.922
<i>and I'm getting the horns
on the ram's head now.</i>

32:13.966 --> 32:18.760
¶ ¶

32:18.804 --> 32:21.054
<i>I'm bending the horns down,</i>

32:21.098 --> 32:24.641
<i>Gonna have, like,
a very organic curve to it.</i>

32:24.685 --> 32:26.226
Oh, [bleep].

32:26.270 --> 32:29.062
[torch clicking]

32:29.106 --> 32:31.606
[bleep].

32:31.650 --> 32:35.110
<i>I run out of oxygen
on my oxy-acetylene torch.</i>

32:35.154 --> 32:39.281
I'm not exactly where I want to
be on the horns, the hammerhead,

32:39.324 --> 32:42.450
and it's starting to wear on me.

32:42.494 --> 32:45.036
<i>I'm just gonna have to come in
in the morning and focus</i>

32:45.080 --> 32:47.664
and hustle and make sure
I'm doing everything right,

32:47.708 --> 32:49.124
don't make any mistakes.

32:49.168 --> 32:50.417
I don't have any room for that.

32:50.460 --> 32:53.420
<i>[rock music]</i>

32:53.463 --> 32:55.130
¶ ¶

32:55.174 --> 32:56.974
- All right, now we're ready
to rock and roll.

32:57.009 --> 32:58.508
Yesterday was a busy day for me.

32:58.552 --> 33:00.302
I got the Damascus
forged for my head,

33:00.345 --> 33:03.805
<i>and I've got it squared
to about the right dimensions.</i>

33:03.849 --> 33:06.016
The hammerhead's gonna start
taking shape for me today.

33:06.059 --> 33:09.436
<i>The langets are pretty much
gonna lock everything in.</i>

33:09.479 --> 33:11.188
¶ ¶

33:11.231 --> 33:13.106
[laughs]

33:13.150 --> 33:17.402
That is cool.

33:17.446 --> 33:19.406
I'm looking at these sharp
corners on these slots,

33:19.448 --> 33:21.156
and I know I'm gonna
have a problem with this

33:21.200 --> 33:22.908
<i>if I try to full quench it.</i>

33:22.951 --> 33:25.911
Where I've put
the langet pockets in there,

33:25.954 --> 33:27.829
that can crack.

33:27.873 --> 33:29.706
It's thinner than everything
else.

33:29.750 --> 33:33.335
I could literally end up
with two pieces of hammer.

33:33.378 --> 33:35.879
I'm gonna do a differential
heat treat on it.

33:35.923 --> 33:37.839
<i>I'm gonna try to harden
the front and harden the back</i>

33:37.883 --> 33:40.008
<i>but leave the middle soft.</i>

33:40.052 --> 33:41.801
<i>If I crack the hammer
while I'm quenching,</i>

33:41.845 --> 33:44.554
<i>that could be disastrous for me.</i>

33:44.598 --> 33:47.557
<i>[rock music]</i>

33:47.601 --> 33:49.517
¶ ¶

33:49.561 --> 33:51.937
<i>- Yesterday I was able to get
the hammerhead finished</i>

33:51.980 --> 33:54.898
with all the detail,
get it quenched.

33:54.942 --> 33:58.193
And today
I'm getting into the handle.

33:58.237 --> 34:00.612
¶ ¶

34:00.656 --> 34:03.865
<i>My plan is to add
some upholstery rivets</i>

34:03.909 --> 34:08.453
<i>down the sides and the front
and back of the handle.</i>

34:08.497 --> 34:12.040
<i>It's gonna be a mix
of unique decorative work</i>

34:12.084 --> 34:14.584
<i>and traditional-style
war hammer</i>

34:14.628 --> 34:16.628
<i>with the spike
and the hammerhead.</i>

34:16.672 --> 34:18.505
It's good to go.

34:18.548 --> 34:21.216
¶ ¶

34:21.260 --> 34:23.551
<i>- Yesterday I was able
to finish up my top cap.</i>

34:23.595 --> 34:25.387
<i>Today I'm gonna focus
on getting everything</i>

34:25.430 --> 34:28.223
finished up
and making it pretty.

34:28.267 --> 34:31.101
All right, I've got some plans
for you today.

34:31.144 --> 34:33.561
Let's see if she's ready
for prime time.

34:33.605 --> 34:36.564
¶ ¶

34:36.608 --> 34:39.901
Whoo! Yeah,
I think that'll work.

34:39.945 --> 34:42.070
No problem.

34:42.114 --> 34:44.239
¶ ¶

34:44.283 --> 34:46.700
<i>Well, I'm real happy
with the way it came out,</i>

34:46.743 --> 34:48.451
<i>the weight, the balance.</i>

34:48.495 --> 34:50.370
I love the way it feels.

34:50.414 --> 34:51.746
I've done everything I can.
I've tested my hammer.

34:51.790 --> 34:53.415
I've made it look nice.

34:53.458 --> 34:57.419
<i>But it's still anybody's
ball game.</i>

35:05.595 --> 35:08.555
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

35:08.598 --> 35:12.559
¶ ¶

35:12.602 --> 35:15.020
- Jeff, Craig, welcome back.

35:15.063 --> 35:16.771
Because your weapons
are war hammers,

35:16.815 --> 35:19.441
we decided to leave the Forge
and bring them to a location

35:19.484 --> 35:22.819
a little bit more benefiting
their medieval style.

35:22.863 --> 35:25.447
You've had five days
to work on your weapons.

35:25.490 --> 35:27.073
How'd it go at your home
forge, Jeff?

35:27.117 --> 35:29.075
- I had a great time
making the hammer.

35:29.119 --> 35:31.036
<i>The horns gave me a little bit
of trouble,</i>

35:31.079 --> 35:33.288
<i>but I like the way it looks.</i>

35:33.332 --> 35:34.873
Overall, I think it's great.

35:34.916 --> 35:37.208
- How'd it go for you, Craig?
- It went good.

35:37.252 --> 35:39.252
<i>I had a little problems
with the langets.</i>

35:39.296 --> 35:41.629
<i>But I got 'em inlaid like
I wanted to, so in the end,</i>

35:41.673 --> 35:42.881
I'm really happy with 'em.

35:42.924 --> 35:44.591
- Well, gents,
your weapons look great,

35:44.634 --> 35:47.218
but looks are
secondary to performance.

35:47.262 --> 35:49.387
We are now gonna
put both your weapons

35:49.431 --> 35:50.889
through three different tests.

35:50.932 --> 35:52.640
First up, the sharpness test.

35:52.684 --> 35:54.059
Dave?

35:54.102 --> 35:55.727
- Gentlemen...

35:55.771 --> 35:58.396
the war hammer was primarily
a close-quarters weapon.

35:58.440 --> 36:01.232
But it was devastating
to anything it went up against,

36:01.276 --> 36:03.985
which occasionally
was a castle door.

36:04.029 --> 36:06.905
So I'm gonna take several
strikes against this oak door,

36:06.948 --> 36:10.867
to see how well the pick
on your weapon penetrates.

36:10.911 --> 36:12.911
Craig, you ready?

36:12.954 --> 36:14.204
- I'm ready.

36:14.247 --> 36:16.414
<i>I see the doors set up.</i>

36:16.458 --> 36:18.917
<i>I'm thinking, "My war hammer's
just gonna demolish this door."</i>

36:18.960 --> 36:21.044
I'm pretty confident
in my hammer.

36:21.088 --> 36:24.047
<i>[tense music]</i>

36:24.091 --> 36:32.091
¶ ¶

36:37.229 --> 36:40.438
- Well, Craig, this really
felt great in my hands.

36:40.482 --> 36:42.315
It's got a nice balance to it.

36:42.359 --> 36:45.777
Your pick... I don't see
any real distortion on it.

36:45.821 --> 36:47.112
The shape of your pick

36:47.155 --> 36:49.614
with that nice drop hook
to the end of it

36:49.658 --> 36:51.116
really penetrated well.

36:51.159 --> 36:53.284
And you could see,
when I got it in that door

36:53.328 --> 36:54.869
how hard it was to remove.

36:54.913 --> 36:56.955
- Yeah.
- Nicely done.

36:56.998 --> 36:58.289
- Appreciate it.
- Beautifully executed.

36:58.333 --> 37:00.208
- Thank you.

37:00.252 --> 37:01.501
- So, Jeff, your turn.
You ready?

37:01.545 --> 37:05.463
- Let's smash it.
- All right.

37:05.507 --> 37:08.466
<i>[rock music]</i>

37:08.510 --> 37:16.510
¶ ¶

37:17.602 --> 37:20.687
[metal clanging]

37:20.730 --> 37:25.316
So... we started losing pieces.

37:25.360 --> 37:27.485
I could tell that they're
on there only decoratively,

37:27.529 --> 37:29.487
so I was able to continue on.

37:29.531 --> 37:31.573
Good thing: head's still
right and tight.

37:31.616 --> 37:33.324
- Right.

37:33.368 --> 37:36.119
- The way your pick
leans out towards the front

37:36.163 --> 37:37.829
gave a lot of penetration.

37:37.873 --> 37:40.498
I was really able to just
blow parts out of this door.

37:40.542 --> 37:41.875
- Mm-hmm.
- Nicely designed.

37:41.918 --> 37:43.251
- Thank you.
- Well-executed.

37:43.295 --> 37:45.003
- Thanks.

37:45.046 --> 37:46.963
- Bladesmiths, now it's time
for the kill test.

37:47.007 --> 37:50.425
War hammers have been known
to deliver piercing blows

37:50.469 --> 37:54.012
into armor and crush
the person behind it.

37:54.055 --> 37:56.347
I will deliver strikes
at this ballistic dummy

37:56.391 --> 37:58.057
that's wearing armor.

37:58.101 --> 38:00.894
Then we can see how much lethal
damage your war hammer can give.

38:00.937 --> 38:02.353
Craig, you're up.
Are you ready?

38:02.397 --> 38:04.022
- I'm ready.
Let's do it.

38:04.065 --> 38:07.025
<i>[rock music]</i>

38:07.068 --> 38:15.068
¶ ¶

38:18.580 --> 38:23.875
- Craig, I love the balance
of this blade, no indentations.

38:23.919 --> 38:28.087
Now let's see how much damage
we put on the dummy.

38:28.131 --> 38:30.381
No visible broken bones,

38:30.425 --> 38:33.051
but that definitely did pierce
the skin.

38:33.094 --> 38:35.512
- Nice.

38:35.555 --> 38:38.056
This will definitely kill.

38:38.099 --> 38:40.016
Nicely done, sir.
- Thank you.

38:40.060 --> 38:41.392
- Jeff, you're up next.
You ready?

38:41.436 --> 38:43.394
- Yes, sir.

38:43.438 --> 38:46.439
<i>The kill test, it's the most
important part to me.</i>

38:46.483 --> 38:49.609
I want it to smash that piece
of plate steel, break some ribs,

38:49.653 --> 38:50.944
and ruin some organs.

38:50.987 --> 38:53.947
<i>[rock music]</i>

38:53.990 --> 39:01.990
¶ ¶

39:05.460 --> 39:08.753
- Well, Jeff, looks like
the other langet did break off.

39:08.797 --> 39:10.171
<i>Do you know what?</i>

39:10.215 --> 39:12.257
This is still very sturdy.

39:12.300 --> 39:15.218
But let's see how much damage
it's done internally.

39:15.262 --> 39:17.178
¶ ¶

39:17.222 --> 39:19.681
He's got some broken ribs right
here, broken bones throughout.

39:19.724 --> 39:21.266
It went all the way through.

39:21.309 --> 39:24.143
And even through armor,
you pierced the skin,

39:24.187 --> 39:26.521
and you caused
some internal damage.

39:26.565 --> 39:29.107
Jeff, your weapon will kill.

39:29.150 --> 39:30.608
- Awesome.
- Good job.

39:30.652 --> 39:32.110
- Thank you.

39:32.153 --> 39:34.279
- Gentlemen,
this is the strength test.

39:34.322 --> 39:37.448
The war hammer was a favorite
on the medieval battlefield.

39:37.492 --> 39:39.284
So I'm gonna
take your war hammer

39:39.327 --> 39:41.119
and to test its strength
and durability,

39:41.162 --> 39:43.621
I'm gonna take several blows
against our stone wall

39:43.665 --> 39:45.373
and see
how much of this I can move.

39:45.417 --> 39:46.958
<i>- You know,
I'm feeling pretty nervous.</i>

39:47.002 --> 39:48.459
I know what it's capable of.

39:48.503 --> 39:49.961
I've worked with it at home.

39:50.005 --> 39:51.296
But still, yeah,
watching somebody else do it,

39:51.339 --> 39:52.630
it's nerve-racking for me.

39:52.674 --> 39:55.633
<i>[tense music]</i>

39:55.677 --> 39:57.302
¶ ¶

40:03.935 --> 40:05.768
- So I'm gonna
take your war hammer,

40:05.812 --> 40:07.604
and to test its strength
and durability,

40:07.647 --> 40:10.231
I'm gonna take several blows
against our stone wall

40:10.275 --> 40:11.983
and see how much of this
I can move.

40:12.027 --> 40:14.193
Craig, you're up.
- All right, let's do it.

40:14.237 --> 40:17.196
<i>[rock music]</i>

40:17.240 --> 40:25.240
¶ ¶

40:27.292 --> 40:30.084
- Wow, that held up really well.

40:30.128 --> 40:32.170
And that's pretty much a hole
I could crawl through.

40:32.213 --> 40:33.963
That'll work.

40:34.007 --> 40:35.298
- Perfect.

40:35.342 --> 40:37.258
- So the handle...
What I do like is,

40:37.302 --> 40:39.761
I could swing it one-handed,
but with two hands,

40:39.804 --> 40:41.971
I could generate a heck
of a lot of energy.

40:42.015 --> 40:43.348
Beautiful job.

40:43.391 --> 40:45.683
- Excellent, excellent.
Thank you.

40:45.727 --> 40:47.644
- Jeff, you're up.

40:47.687 --> 40:49.020
- Let's knock it down.

40:49.064 --> 40:52.023
<i>[rock music]</i>

40:52.067 --> 40:56.444
¶ ¶

40:58.948 --> 41:00.615
- It's long,
and when I was swinging,

41:00.659 --> 41:02.283
it was way out in front of me

41:02.327 --> 41:05.119
as opposed
to being close and in control.

41:05.163 --> 41:06.954
Shot some sparks off.

41:06.998 --> 41:08.790
<i>- Right, I seen that.</i>

41:08.833 --> 41:10.583
- All in all,
a good performance.

41:10.627 --> 41:12.669
- Great.

41:12.712 --> 41:15.380
- Well, gentlemen, you've given
the judges a lot to consider.

41:15.423 --> 41:17.924
We'll see you back at the Forge.

41:17.967 --> 41:20.301
<i>[tense music]</i>

41:20.345 --> 41:24.597
Craig, Jeff, you were given
five days at your home forge

41:24.641 --> 41:26.599
to fabricate war hammers,

41:26.643 --> 41:30.186
and you both performed very well
in our weapons tests.

41:30.230 --> 41:33.356
But there can only be one
"Forged in Fire" champion.

41:33.400 --> 41:36.025
J?
- Craig, that's a great piece.

41:36.069 --> 41:37.860
<i>Your fit
and finish is outstanding,</i>

41:37.904 --> 41:39.987
<i>and I love the fact that you
can see</i>

41:40.031 --> 41:42.824
<i>the differential heat treat
in the hammerhead and beak.</i>

41:42.867 --> 41:46.119
There is a slight delamination
in one corner of the hammer face

41:46.162 --> 41:49.497
that does concern me
a little bit, though.

41:49.541 --> 41:51.666
- Jeff, there's a word that
they call "functional art."

41:51.710 --> 41:53.626
You have it right there.

41:53.670 --> 41:58.005
<i>The beautiful design you have
of that hammer is amazing.</i>

41:58.049 --> 42:00.299
My only concern was,
during the kill test,

42:00.343 --> 42:01.926
<i>the langlet came off.</i>

42:01.970 --> 42:04.303
It could've been better secured.

42:04.347 --> 42:07.473
- Gentlemen,
it was not an easy decision.

42:07.517 --> 42:10.101
Both of your weapons are superb,

42:10.145 --> 42:13.646
but there can only be
one "Forged in Fire" champion.

42:13.690 --> 42:15.857
<i>[tense music]</i>

42:15.900 --> 42:18.568
Craig, you are
the "Forged in Fire" champion.

42:18.611 --> 42:20.403
Congratulations.
- Thank you.

42:20.447 --> 42:24.031
- Jeff, your weapon
did not make the cut.

42:24.075 --> 42:26.242
- Jeff, with pieces coming
off of it, and the fact

42:26.286 --> 42:29.203
that it can only really be used
as a two-handed weapon,

42:29.247 --> 42:33.124
those things added together
started to become a problem.

42:33.168 --> 42:34.542
- Please surrender
your war hammer.

42:34.586 --> 42:36.210
<i>[tense music]</i>

42:36.254 --> 42:38.379
- I respected the judges'
decision.

42:38.423 --> 42:41.132
If I knew what I know now,
I would've changed some things.

42:41.176 --> 42:42.717
<i>[rock music]</i>

42:42.761 --> 42:44.385
- Craig, congratulations.

42:44.429 --> 42:45.928
You are the "Forged in Fire"
champion.

42:45.972 --> 42:48.222
- It was a fun challenge.

42:48.266 --> 42:53.352
- Craig, you will also be
receiving a check for $10,000.

42:53.396 --> 42:55.646
- I'm just stoked.
It's crazy.

42:55.690 --> 42:57.899
This experience,
it was a grueling process.

42:57.942 --> 42:59.734
You know, I got to do something
that I really enjoyed

42:59.778 --> 43:01.319
and I'm really passionate about.

43:01.362 --> 43:03.321
I came here for my son.

43:03.364 --> 43:04.697
I mean, it doesn't get any
better than that.

43:04.741 --> 43:07.742
<i>[rock music]</i>
